Load Packages

We’re loading four packages today: the Tidyverse (for general data science goodness and visualizations), janitor (for data cleaning), arcos (for loading WaPo opioid data), scales (for cleaning up visualization axes), ggrepel (for better scatterplot point labels).

We’re also going to load a new package, tidycensus, for pulling in data from the U.S. Census.

Set ARCOS R Package API Key

For this exercise, we will be working with subsets of the DEA’s ARCOS database, which documented shipments of 76 billion opioid pills between 2006 and 2012, during the peak of the opioid epidemic.

The data was obtained after a lengthy legal battle by the Washington Post and the Charleston Gazette-Mail, and released by the Washington Post in raw and aggregated form. Washington Post “Digging into the DEA’s pain pill database” page.

A data dictionary is available here: ARCOS Registrant Handbook.

We’re going to load opioid data exclusively from the arcos R package API ARCOS API produced by the Washington Post, instead of uploading csvs and tsvs.

Remember, we need to store a password of sorts – called an API key – that will give us permission to access their data. Here’s a list of API keys that will work.

Store the key first.

# store one of our API keys as an object called key
key <- "uO4EK6I"

Load the data you’ll need for this package and clean up the column names.

arcos_county_pills_per_year <- summarized_county_annual(key = key) %>%

Build Exploratory Visualizations

Task: Build an exploratory visualization to show year-over-year pill totals in Logan County, West Virginia between 2006 and 2012. It should have the following attributes: * Chart Type: a bar chart, with one bar per year between 2006 and 2012. Make the bars forest green. * Axes: years on the x axis, pill totals on the y axis, with proper axis labels. The number for each year should be shown. Put commas in the pill totals on the y axis, so they’re readable.
* Text: put a descriptive title, subtitle and source line. The title should describe the main takeaway.

You should also write up a few sentences explaining the trend in a bit more detail.

logan_pills_per_year <- arcos_county_pills_per_year %>%
  filter(buyer_state == "WV", buyer_county == "LOGAN") %>%
  select(year, dosage_unit)
  ggplot(logan_pills_per_year) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", aes(year, dosage_unit), fill="forest green") +
  labs(x="Year", y="Total pills", title="Logan County Pill Shipments 2006-2012", subtitle = "Total pills shipped to Logan County by year", caption = "Source: DEA ARCOS database, via Washington Post") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(2006, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma)

# It looks like in Logan County the total pills per year were pretty consistent with lower numbers in 2006, 2007, 2010 and 2012. The number rose steadily up until 2009 then dipped in 2010 and rose again in 2011 with another dip in 2012.

Task: Build an exploratory visualization to show how year-over-year pill totals in Logan County, West Virginia between 2006 and 2012 compare to five other West Virginia counties with high levels of opioid shipments. It should have the following attributes: * Chart Type: six “small multiple” bar charts, arranged in a 3 x 2 grid. There should be one bar chart per county. * Counties: one chart per county for the following counties: Kanawha, Cabell, Mingo, Raleigh, Logan and Wood. * Axes: years on the x axis, pill totals on the y axis, with proper axis labels. The number for each year should be shown. Put commas in the pill totals on the y axis, so they’re readable. Rotate the year labels so they’re readable.
* Text: put a descriptive title, subtitle and source line. The title should describe the main takeaway.

You should also write up a few sentences explaining the trends in a bit more detail.

wv_pills_per_year <- arcos_county_pills_per_year %>%
  filter(buyer_state == "WV", (buyer_county %in% c("KANAWHA", "CABELL", "MINGO", "RALEIGH","LOGAN", "WOOD"))) %>%
  select(buyer_county, year, dosage_unit)
  ggplot(wv_pills_per_year) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", aes(year, dosage_unit, fill=buyer_county)) +
  labs(x="Year", y="Total pills", title="Varying usage of opioids in WV Counties", subtitle = "Total pills per year shipped to Cabell, Kanawha, Logan, Mingo,\nRaleigh and Wood County", caption = "Source: DEA ARCOS database, via Washington Post", fill="County") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(2006, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma) +
  facet_wrap(nrow=2, . ~ buyer_county) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  guides(fill="none")

# Kanawha, Raleigh and Wood County all had a steady growth from 2006-2012. Cabell and Logan had a steady growth with a slight dip in 2009. Mingo County was the only one where the number of opioids dipped significantly after 2008.

Task (This one is more challenging): Build a scatterplot that explores the relationship between the following two factors for Maryland counties: the pills per person rate (not total pills, but pills per person) for a county in 2012 and the county’s median household income in 2012.

It should have the following attributes: * each point labeled with the county name. * a blue “line of best fit” running through the data showing the trend line.
* a title that explains what you’re seeing in the data. Is there a trend?

To get the data we’re going to use for median household income, we’re going to use the tidycensus package in R, which allows us to pull data directly from the U.S. Census’ API.

Here’s the code you’ll need to pull it in.

#Get Median Household Income Data for each Maryland County from Tidycensus 
# Help using TidyCensus, including how to find variables of interest. https://walkerke.github.io/tidycensus/articles/basic-usage.html

# Define census api key.  I'm including mine here.  You may need to get your own. https://api.census.gov/data/key_signup.html

census_api_key("549950d36c22ff16455fe196bbbd01d63cfbe6cf")

# Store a table with the median household income value for each county using the get_acs() function.  ACS is short for American Community Survey, one of two main census products. In the table that's loaded in, the :estimate" is the median household income for that county, averaged over 5 years ending in 2012. 

county_median_household_income <- get_acs(geography = "county", variables = c("B19013_001"), survey="acs5", year = 2012)

# How did I get the variables?  I pulled in a table from the tidycensus package that lists all of the thousands of variables available through the census.  Load the table below and view it.  Use filters in the R Viewer window to find things you might want to use later. You can also find table and variable numbers at https://data.census.gov/cedsci/.

acs_variables <- load_variables(2012, "acs5", cache = TRUE)

# Filter just for Maryland counties
md_county_median_household_income <- county_median_household_income %>%
  filter(str_detect(NAME, ", Maryland"))
maryland_pills_2012 <- arcos_county_pills_per_year %>%
  filter(buyer_state == "MD", year=="2012") %>%
  select(buyer_county, year, dosage_unit, countyfips)
md_population_2012 <- county_population(key = key) %>%
  clean_names() %>%
  filter(buyer_state == "MD", year=="2012") %>%
  select(buyer_county, population)
maryland_2012 <- maryland_pills_2012 %>%
  inner_join(md_population_2012, by=("buyer_county")) %>%
  select(buyer_county, dosage_unit, population)
md_pills_per_person <- maryland_2012 %>%
  group_by(buyer_county) %>%
  mutate(total_pills = sum(dosage_unit))%>%
  mutate(pills_per_person = total_pills/population)
md_pills_county <- md_pills_per_person %>%
  inner_join(maryland_pills_2012, by=("buyer_county"))
# Changing the name to combine
md_county_median_household_income <-
rename(md_county_median_household_income, countyfips = GEOID)
final_md_object <- md_pills_county%>%
  inner_join(md_county_median_household_income, by="countyfips")
ggplot(final_md_object) +
  geom_point(aes(pills_per_person, estimate)) +
  labs(x="Avg. Pills per Person", y="2012 Median Income", title="MD Counties Income and Opioid Relationship", caption = "Source: DEA ARCOS database, via Washington Post", fill="buyer_county") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = comma) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(pills_per_person, estimate), method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  geom_text_repel(aes(pills_per_person, estimate, label=buyer_county))
